image crop by mask is an easy way to resize the image to keep only the subject to anim and remove the useless pixels, the less the pixels, the faster the generation. this node avoid to use a third party software to resize your image and is more efficient that the basic crop image node.

how to use.
1. unbypass of course
2. right click on the image ---> open in mask editor
3. just do 4 points at the top, left, right and bottom of the subject, everything outside this points will be croped
(you can just do 2 point top-left and bottom-right, works too)
4. save

it's optional, bypass if you don't need it or you'll get an error.

<------------------------------------------
the most important thing ! use this and navigate between the lasts and firsts frames with the arrow keys to understand what happen between your loop end and start. the loop can:
-start a new loop but don't have enough frames to end. it's the best case easy to correct by skipping the surplus frames.
-end to soon, pretty hard to corect, require sometime to skip a lot of frames to find to close frames, results are not the best.
-freeze at end, the movement is almost non-existent at end, in some case it can be really hard to save with a natural movement due to a light position change of the character but sometimes it's not a problem, middle hard.
-do random things, random hard i guess....

how it work: i use the same image at start and end to try to do a loop with WanStartEndFramesNative. but it's not perfect.

so, i took the last and first frame of the loop and use the interpolation to generate the missing frames and close the loop.
this work well but it's very linear and not natural, this is why i say later to be gentle.

the point of the frame skip, the last and first frames will be close, but don't loop naturally, so i will create a gap on purpose to be filled with the interpolations frames.

i use the preview image to choose 2 close frames to process, a tutorial video is available in the examples (on the prvious workflow but usage is the same).

How to use
note: stay in fixed seed and keep the group bypassed for now.

1- launch the run
2- once done, if the the video "jump" use the 3 sliders to find the sweet spot, move gently the slider and re-run, the video will not be generate again due to fixed seed, only the video combine will be updated. skip first and last frames and do test, be gentle with the interpolation 2 or 3 is enough. it's usually better to skip at least 1 frame at start, so, the movement is already initiated. the min for last frame is set to 1, the original last frame is the same as the first but in bad quality. the min to interpolation is set to 2 or you'll not have middle frame.
3- once you find the sweet spot, turn the group on, and launch a last re-run, the video will be interpolated and saved.
4- once over, think to turn the group off again and set all the sliders to min value, you can now manually change the seed or use another image.

note: sometimes it's pretty hard to get a decent result, just change the seed and restart ;)

splitsigmas and basic scheduler:
split sigmas is generally half the number of steps but not always true, you can see things like this:
20 steps split sigmas set to 6.
6 steps wil be used to create the movement in low quality, 14 will be used to refine this low quality quality movement in high quality vid.
i've got awesome quality with this settings so i let it like this, do your tests.

end interpolation frames.
use the last and first frames at the frame skip output to create the missing frames between, first and last frames are auto-skipped, only the middles ones are used to avoid frames duplication.

you can play with this parameters to influence on the final vid speed or fluidity.
how it work:
for this example we wil use a 20 frames generated vid.

-final interpolation slider: if the slider is set to 3 that mean the interpolation will use 1 image to create 3, the output vid will now have 20x3=60 frames.

-fps slider: now we have 60 frames, ok, we can do a short and quick video, really smooth at 60 fps, the video duration will be 1 second, or a 30fps video, a little less smooth, but slower and longer, 60 frames @ 30 fps mean (60 frames/30fps)= 2seconds vid.

you can see on the example video an interpolation 4/60fps vid is the same speed that an interpolation 2/30fps vid but smoother. the vid play 2x faster but she have 2x more frames. (she will also be heavier but not necessarily 2x, depending on a lot of factor, not the point here)

Warning, playing with final interpolation slider will force the rife vfi module to re-process the images, it's not a problem, you just need to wait a little. to high interpolation can ruin quality or create artifact on fast movement.
playing with the fps slider just relaunch the video combine.
you can turn the save button off during your test to don't save all the videos, just don't forget to turn it on again and re-run  once you've got a good result (yeah i'm dumb enough to forget and relaunch a gen without save).
